trans-unit.source: unsafe fn also acts like an unsafe {} block around the code inside the function. This means it is not just a signal to the caller, but also promises that the preconditions for the operations inside the function are upheld. Mixing these two meanings can be confusing and proposals exist to use unsafe {} blocks inside such functions when making unsafe operations.
trans-unit.target: unsafe fn 은 함수 내부의 코드 주변에서 unsafe {} 블록 처럼 작동합니다. 이는 호출자에게 보내는 신호일뿐만 아니라 함수 내부의 작업에 대한 전제 조건이 유지된다는 것을 의미합니다. 이 두 가지 의미를 혼합하면 혼란 스러울 수 있으며 unsafe 작업을 수행 할 때 이러한 함수 내에서 unsafe {} 블록 을 사용하기 위한 제안 이 존재 합니다.

trans-unit.source: unsafe fn: calling this function means abiding by a contract the compiler cannot enforce.
trans-unit.target: unsafe fn :이 함수를 호출한다는 것은 컴파일러가 시행 할 수없는 계약을 준수하는 것을 의미합니다.

trans-unit.source: unsafe impl: the contract necessary to implement the trait has been checked by the programmer and is guaranteed to be respected.
trans-unit.target: unsafe impl : 특성을 구현하는 데 필요한 계약이 프로그래머에 의해 확인되었으며 존중이 보장됩니다.

trans-unit.source: unsafe trait: implementing the trait means abiding by a contract the compiler cannot enforce.
trans-unit.target: unsafe trait : 구현하는 trait 컴파일러가 적용 할 수없는 계약을 준수하는 방법을.

trans-unit.source: unsafe {}: the contract necessary to call the operations inside the block has been checked by the programmer and is guaranteed to be respected.
trans-unit.target: unsafe {} : 블록 내에서 작업을 호출하는 데 필요한 계약이 프로그래머에 의해 확인되었으며 존중이 보장됩니다.

trans-unit.source: Interior mutability is a design pattern in Rust that allows you to mutate data even when there are immutable references to that data; normally, this action is disallowed by the borrowing rules. trans-unit.source: Mutex is an abbreviation for mutual exclusion, as in, a mutex allows only one thread to access some data at any given time. trans-unit.source: Note: this module is unstable and is designed in RFC 2504, and you can learn more about its status in the tracking issue.

Nul terminators and implicit string lengths - Often, C strings are nul-terminated, i.e., they have a \0 character at the end. The length of a string buffer is not stored, but has to be calculated; to compute the length of a string, C code must manually call a function like strlen() for char-based strings, or wcslen() for wchar_t-based ones. Those functions return the number of characters in the string excluding the nul terminator, so the buffer length is really len+1 characters. Rust strings don't have a nul terminator; their length is always stored and does not need to be calculated. While in Rust accessing a string's length is a O(1) operation (because the length is stored); in C it is an O(length) operation because the length needs to be computed by scanning the string for the nul terminator.
